INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(220,'equation','eq:ZZZZ-7','\\begin{eqnarray*} \\cos^2 \\theta &=&\\frac{1}{2}\\left(1+\\cos 2\\theta\\right)\\\\ \\sin^2 \\theta &=&\\frac{1}{2}\\left(1-\\cos 2\\theta\\right)   \\end{eqnarray*}',2,3,10);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(221,'index',NULL,'Trigonometric identities',2,3,10);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(222,'paragraph',NULL,'Clearly, the sine and cosine functions are very closely related. This often leads to opportunities for simplification of expressions involving both sine and cosine functions.  In calculus, we have the interesting property that the sine and cosine functions are derivatives of each other: <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? \\frac{d \\sin \\theta}{d \\theta}= \\cos \\theta \\quad  \and \\quad  \\frac{d \\cos \\theta}{d \\theta}= -\\sin \\theta "/></div> That is, the cosine function gives the slope of the sine function, and the sine function is the negative of the slope of the cosine function. In trigonometry, there are many  identities that can be used in simplifying expressions involving combinations of sinusoidal signals. Table <a href="tab:identities" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> gives a brief table of <i> trigonometric identities</i>  that will be useful. Recall from your study of trigonometry that these identities are not independent; e.g., identity 3 can be obtained from identity 4 by substituting <span class="ITS_HTML">&alpha;=&beta;=&theta;</span>. <div class="ITS_TABLE"><center><div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{tabular}{|c|l|} \\hline \\multicolumn{1}{|c|}{Number} & \\multicolumn{1}{|c|}{Equation} \\\\ \\hline\\hline 1 & \\sin^2\\theta + \\cos^2\\theta = 1  \\rule[-6pt]{0pt}{18pt} \\\\ \\hline 2 & \\cos 2\\theta =  \\cos^2\\theta - \\sin^2\\theta  \\rule[-6pt]{0pt}{18pt}  \\\\ \\hline 3 & \\sin 2\\theta =2\\sin \\theta \\cos \\theta \\rule[-4pt]{0pt}{15pt} \\\\ \\hline 4 & \\sin(\\alpha\\pm\\beta) = \\sin \\alpha \\cos \\beta \\pm \\cos \\alpha \\sin\\beta  \\rule[-4pt]{0pt}{15pt} \\\\ \\hline 5 &  \\cos (\\alpha \\pm \\beta) = \\cos \\alpha \\cos \\beta \\mp \\sin \\alpha  \\sin \\beta  \\rule[-4pt]{0pt}{15pt} \\\\ \\hline \\end{tabular}"/></div></center><br><div class="ITS_Caption">Some basic trigonometric identities.</span></div></div> Also, these identities can be combined to derive other identities. For example, combining identity 1 with identity 2 leads to the identities <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{eqnarray*} \\cos^2 \\theta &=&\\frac{1}{2}\\left(1+\\cos 2\\theta\\right)\\\\ \\sin^2 \\theta &=&\\frac{1}{2}\\left(1-\\cos 2\\theta\\right)   \\end{eqnarray*}"/></div> A more extensive table of trigonometric identities may be found in any book on trigonometry or in a book of mathematical tables.','2','3','10');
