INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(424,'index',NULL,'Sampling period',2,5,1);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(425,'paragraph',NULL,'<h3 class="ITS_BOOK">2-4  Sampling and Plotting Sinusoids</h3> All of the plots of sinusoids in this chapter were created using MATLAB. This had to be done with care, because MATLAB  deals only with discrete signals represented by row or column matrices, but we are actually plotting a continuous function <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span>. For example, if we wish to plot a function such as <div class="ITS_EQUATION"> x(t) = 20 cos(2&pi;(40) t -0.4&pi;  ) </div> which is shown in Fig. <a href="fig:plot-of-sine-wave" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, we must evaluate <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> at a discrete set of times, <span class="ITS_HTML">t<sub>n</sub> = nT<sub>s</sub></span>, where <span class="ITS_HTML">n</span> is an integer. If we do so, we  obtain the sequence of samples <div class="ITS_EQUATION"> x(nT<sub>s</sub>) = 20 cos(80&pi; nT<sub>s</sub> -0.4&pi;  ) </div> where <span class="ITS_HTML">T<sub>s</sub></span> is called the <i> sample spacing</i>  or  <span class="ITS_blue">sampling period,</span> and <span class="ITS_HTML">n</span> is an integer. When plotting the function using the <tt>plot</tt> function in MATLAB, we must provide a pair of row or column vectors, one containing the time values and the other the computed function values to be plotted. For example, the MATLAB  statements','2','5','1');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(426,'math',NULL,'-0.035',2,5,2);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(427,'math',NULL,'0.025',2,5,2);
