INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(2039,'subsection','sec:Ideal-Reconstruction','Ideal Reconstruction',4,2,38);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(2040,'subsection','sec:Ideal-Reconstruction','Ideal Reconstruction',4,2,38);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(2041,'index',NULL,'Ideal reconstruction',4,2,38);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(2042,'index',NULL,'Ideal discrete-to-continuous (D-to-C) converter',4,2,38);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(2043,'index',NULL,'Interpolation',4,2,38);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(2044,'paragraph',NULL,'<h3 class="ITS_BOOK">4-0.9  Ideal Reconstruction</h3> The sampling theorem suggests that a process exists for reconstructing a continuous-time signal from its samples. This reconstruction process would undo the C-to-D conversion so it is called D-to-C conversion.  The ideal discrete-to-continuous (D-to-C) converter  is depicted in Fig. <a href="fig:DC-converter" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>. <div class="ITS_Image"><center><img src="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch04/Fig04-06_D2C_block_diagram.png" alt="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch04/Fig04-06_D2C_block_diagram.png"></center><br><div class="ITS_Caption">Block diagram of the ideal discrete-to-continuous (D-to-C) converter  when the sampling rate is <span class="ITS_HTML">f<sub>s</sub> = 1/T<sub>s</sub></span>. The output signal must satisfy <span class="ITS_HTML">y(n T<sub>s</sub>) = y[n]</span>.</span></div></div> Since the  sampling process of the ideal C-to-D converter is defined by the substitution <span class="ITS_HTML">t = n/&fnof;<sub>s</sub></span> as in <a href="eq:ideal-C2D-converter" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, we would expect the same relationship to govern the ideal D-to-C converter, i.e., <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?y(t) = \\left . \\rule[-1ex]{0pt}{3ex} y[n]\\right |_{n=f_s t} \\quad   -\\infty < n < \\infty"/></div> but this substitution is <i>only</i> true when <span class="ITS_HTML">y(t)</span> is a sum of sinusoids. In that special case where <span class="ITS_HTML">y[n]</span> consists of one or more discrete-time sinusoids, such as <span class="ITS_HTML">y[n] =Acos(2&pi; &fnof;<sub>0</sub> n T<sub>s</sub> +&phi;)</span>,  we can  use the substitution in <a href="eq:ideal-D2C-converter" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> to produce <span class="ITS_HTML">y(t)=Acos(2&pi; &fnof;<sub>0</sub> t +&phi;)</span> at the D-to-C output.  This is convenient because we obtain a mathematical formula for <span class="ITS_HTML">y(t)</span>, but if we only have a sequence of numbers for <span class="ITS_HTML">y[n]</span> that was obtained by sampling, and we do not know the formula for <span class="ITS_HTML">y[n]</span> or there is no simple formula for the signal, things are not so simple. An actual D-to-A converter involves more than the substitution <a href="eq:ideal-D2C-converter" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, because it must also &ldquo;fill in&rdquo; the signal values between the sampling times, <span class="ITS_HTML">t<sub>n</sub> = n T<sub>s</sub></span>. In Section <a href="sec:DC-conversion" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> we will see how <span class="ITS_blue">interpolation</span>  can be used to build an A-to-D converter that <i>approximates</i> the behavior of the ideal C-to-D converter. Later on in Chapter <a href="chap:FourierTransformApplications" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, we will use Fourier transform theory to show how to build better A-to-D converters by incorporating a lowpass (electronic) filter.','4','2','38');
