INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(5902,'subsection','sec:Bhead-ZZZZ-239','Impulse Response of a Second-Order IIR System',8,10,23);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(5903,'subsection','sec:Bhead-ZZZZ-239','Impulse Response of a Second-Order IIR System',8,10,23);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(5904,'paragraph',NULL,'<h3 class="ITS_BOOK">8-8.7  Impulse Response of a Second-Order IIR System</h3> We have derived the general  \ZT\ system function for the second-order filter <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="equation" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?H(z) = \\frac{B(z)}{A(z)} = \\frac{b_0 + b_1 z^{-1} + b_2 z^{-2}}{1 - a_1 z^{-1} - a_2 z^{-2}}"/></div> and we have seen that the denominator polynomial <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?A(z)"/> has two roots that define the poles of the second-order filter. Expressing <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?H(z)"/> in terms of the poles gives <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="equation" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?H(z) = \\frac{b_0 + b_1 z^{-1} + b_2 z^{-2}}{(1 - p_1 z^{-1}) (1 - p_2 z^{-1})}"/></div> Using the partial fraction expansion technique developed in Section <a href="sec:8-7" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, we can express the system function <a href="eq:2nd-order-hz" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> as \CDROMref{IIR Filtering} <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? H(z) = (-b_2/a_2) + \\frac{A_1}{1-p_1 z^{-1}} + \\frac{A_2}{1-p_2 z^{-1}} "/></div> where <span class="ITS_HTML">A<sub>1</sub></span> and <span class="ITS_HTML">A<sub>2</sub></span> can be evaluated by <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? A_k = H(z)(1-p_kz^{-1}) |_{z=p_k}"/>. Therefore, the impulse response will have the form <div class="ITS_EQUATION"> h[n] = (-b<sub>2</sub>/a<sub>2</sub>)&delta;[n] + A<sub>1</sub> (p<sub>1</sub>)<sup>n</sup> u[n] + A<sub>2</sub> (p<sub>2</sub>)<sup>n</sup> u[n] </div> Furthermore, the poles may both be real or they may be a pair of complex conjugates.  We will examine these two cases separately.','8','10','23');
