INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(6781,'paragraph',NULL,'If we substitute the functions <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> and <span class="ITS_HTML">h(t)</span> into <a href="eq:conv_int" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, we obtain <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?y(t) = \\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} e^{-\\tau}u(\\tau) u(t-\\tau -1)  d\\tau"/></div> which is certainly a correct form, but one that still needs a lot of work. In particular, this form does not make it obvious how the limits of integration  depend on <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span>.  The key to efficient and correct evaluation of a convolution integral of this type is to draw an auxiliary sketch of the two functions whose product is the integrand of the convolution integral.  The sketch of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?h(\\tau)"/> is easy; it is just the same graph as <span class="ITS_HTML">h(t)</span> with the axis relabeled. The sketch of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(t-\\tau)"/>, however, is less obvious, but if we proceed systematically, it is also easily done.  To see the steps, consider Fig. <a href="fig:flipping" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>.  Figure <a href="fig:flipping" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(a) shows <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(\\tau)"/>, which is obtained from Fig. <a href="fig:x_and_h" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> by simply relabeling the horizontal axis. Figure <a href="fig:flipping" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(b) shows <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?g(\\tau)=x(-\\tau)"/>, which is the time-reversed version of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(\\tau)"/>.  (We introduce the new symbol <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?g(\\tau)"/> simply to emphasize that the time-reversed function is really just a new function of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tau"/>.)  Finally, in Fig. <a href="fig:flipping" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(c) we show the function <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?g(\\tau)"/> with its time origin shifted by <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span>.  Remember that as far as the dummy variable of integration <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tau"/> is concerned, <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span> is a constant. Now from the definition of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?g(\\tau)"/>, we obtain <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? g(\\tau-t) = x(-(\\tau-t)) = x(t-\\tau) "/></div> i.e., the desired function <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(t-\\tau)"/> is obtained by first time-reversing <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(\\tau)"/> and then shifting the result by <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span>. Thus, to plot or sketch the graph of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(t-\\tau)"/>, we must follow the two steps detailed in Fig. <a href="fig:flipping" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>: \ben <li> flip <span class="ITS_HTML">x(&sdot;)</span> with respect to the origin <li>  then shift the <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tau"/>-origin to <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span>. </ol> \iffalse or we can go directly to the answer by noting that we can simply shift the origin of the graph of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(\\tau)"/> to the point <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span> on the <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tau"/> axis and then &ldquo;flip&rdquo; the graph around the point <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tau=t"/>. Whichever method we use, \fi We will generally have to do this for many values of <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span>. \figurepsAltScale{0.9}{Chapter09/art/flipping} {Illustration of determining <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(t-\\tau)"/> in evaluating convolution: (a) Input signal <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(\\tau)"/>. (b) Time reversed input signal <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(-\\tau)"/>. (c) Time reversed input signal shifted by <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span> on the <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tau"/> axis (shown for <span class="ITS_HTML">t=3</span>).  The gray axis indicates a change from <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span> to <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tau"/>.  }','9','8','5');
