INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7263,'math',NULL,'|\\alpha|<1',9,10,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7264,'math',NULL,'t=\\infty',9,10,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7265,'math',NULL,'|\\alpha|<1',9,10,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7266,'paragraph',NULL,'When echoes and reverberation occur, it might be necessary to &ldquo;recover&rdquo; <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> from <span class="ITS_HTML">y(t)</span>.  When we study Fourier analysis later in Chapter <a href="chap:Fourier_trans" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, we will be able to understand when it is possible to do this in the general case. However, for a single echo it is possible to recover <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> if one simple condition is satisfied. Indeed, now we will show that it may be possible to recover <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> by simply passing the available signal <span class="ITS_HTML">y(t)</span> through another LTI system. Such a system would be called an <span class="ITS_blue">inverse system</span> for the system whose impulse response is <span class="ITS_HTML">h(t)</span>. The operation that we wish to perform is depicted in Fig. <a href="fig:inverse_filtering" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, \figurepsAltScale{\SCALE}{Chapter09/art/cascade_echo_inv}% {Using an LTI system to compensate for an echo. } \iffalse \begin{figure}[htb]  \thicklines \setlength{\unitlength}{.6456in} \begin{picture}(5,1.2) {\small \put(0,.6){\vector(1,0){1}} \put(1,.2){\framebox(1,.8){\shortstack{Echo\\ System \\<span class="ITS_HTML">h(t)</span>}}} \put(2,.6){\vector(1,0){.8}} \put(2.8,.2){\framebox(1,.8){\shortstack{Inverse  \\ System \\ <span class="ITS_HTML">h<sub>i</sub>(t)</span>}}} \put(3.8,.6){\vector(1,0){1}} \put(.8,0){\dashbox{.05}(3.2,1.2)} \put(0,.7){\makebox(0,0)[bl]{<span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span>}} \put(0,.5){\makebox(0,0)[tl]{<span class="ITS_HTML">&delta;(t)</span>}} \put(2.4,.7){\makebox(0,0)[bc]{<span class="ITS_HTML">y(t)</span>}} \put(2.4,.5){\makebox(0,0)[tc]{<span class="ITS_HTML">h(t)</span>}} \put(4.8,.7){\makebox(0,0)[bc]{<span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span>}} \put(4.8,.5){\makebox(0,0)[tc]{\shortstack[l]{<span class="ITS_HTML">h(t) *h<sub>i</sub>(t)</span>\\<span class="ITS_HTML">=&delta;(t)</span>}}} } \end{picture}   Using an LTI system to compensate for an echo. \end{figure} \fi which shows that the goal of the cascade system is to obtain an overall system whose impulse response is a single impulse.  If we write the convolution for the second system in Fig. <a href="fig:inverse_filtering" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, and also substitute the definition of the first system <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} x(t) = y(t)*h_i(t) &= [x(t)*h(t)]*h_i(t)\\nonumber\\\\ & = x(t)*[h(t)*h_i(t)]  \\end{align}"/></div> then we can solve <a href="eq:inverse-convolution" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> for <span class="ITS_HTML">h<sub>i</sub>(t)</span> by recalling the identity element of convolution <span class="ITS_HTML"></span> x(t) =  x(t) \ast \delta(t) <span class="ITS_HTML"></span> which leads to <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} \\delta (t) &= h(t)*h_i(t)\\\\ &= [\\delta(t)+\\alpha \\delta(t-t_d)]*h_i(t) \\end{align}"/></div> To find the inverse system, we must solve <a href="eq:inv_filt_equation" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> for <span class="ITS_HTML">h<sub>i</sub>(t)</span>.  At this point, we have virtually no tools for solving such convolution equations; however, some intuition and trial-and-error can be used to uncover the solution. First, note that <span class="ITS_HTML">h<sub>i</sub>(t)</span> must contain an impulse because we have one on the left-hand side of <a href="eq:inv_filt_equation" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>.  Also, note that we are trying to cancel the echo of size <span class="ITS_HTML">&alpha;</span> at delay <span class="ITS_HTML">t<sub>d</sub></span> so let&lsquo;s try including an impulse with size <span class="ITS_HTML">-&alpha;</span> at delay <span class="ITS_HTML">t<sub>d</sub></span>; i.e., we propose <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? \\tilde{h}_i(t)=\\delta(t)-\\alpha \\delta(t-t_d) "/></div> for the inverse system. Substituting this for <span class="ITS_HTML">h<sub>i</sub>(t)</span> in <a href="eq:inv_filt_equation" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> gives <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align*} h(t)*\\tilde{h}_i(t)& =  [\\delta(t)+\\alpha \\delta(t-t_d)]*[\\delta(t)-\\alpha \\delta(t-t_d)] \\\\ & =  \\delta(t) - \\alpha^2 \\delta(t-2t_d) \\end{align*}"/></div> We have gotten rid of the echo of size <span class="ITS_HTML">&alpha;</span> at time <span class="ITS_HTML">t<sub>d</sub></span>, but replaced it with an echo of size <span class="ITS_HTML">-&alpha;<sup>2</sup></span> at time <span class="ITS_HTML">2t<sub>d</sub></span>. This might be an improvement if <span class="ITS_HTML">|&alpha;|<1</span> because the echo size will be smaller, but we still have not completely removed the echo. What would get rid of the echo at  <span class="ITS_HTML">2t<sub>d</sub></span>?  How about adding a second term to our proposed <span class="ITS_HTML">h<sub>i</sub>(t)</span>?  Perhaps we should add another impulse at <span class="ITS_HTML">2t<sub>d</sub></span>, as in <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? \\tilde{h}_i(t)=\\delta(t)-\\alpha \\delta(t-t_d)+ \\alpha^2 \\delta(t-2t_d) "/></div> which then produces <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? h(t)*\\tilde{h}_i(t)= \\delta(t) + \\alpha^3\\delta(t-3t_d) "/></div> As before, if <span class="ITS_HTML">|&alpha;|<1</span> the remaining echo will be smaller. If we keep on doing this, we are led to the solution <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?h_i(t)=\\sum_{k=0}^{\\infty} (-\\alpha)^k \\delta(t-kt_d)"/></div> which is the correct one because it will push the remaining echo off to <span class="ITS_HTML">t=&infin;</span> and the echo amplitude will be reduced to zero if <span class="ITS_HTML">|&alpha;|<1</span>.','9','10','4');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7267,'math',NULL,'\\delta(t)',9,10,5);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7268,'paragraph',NULL,'<div class="ITS_EXE"><div class="ITS_EXE_logo">Exercise:</div> Substitute <a href="eq:gen_solution" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> into <a href="eq:inv_filt_equation" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> and show that all the impulses that result on the right-hand side of the equation cancel except the term <span class="ITS_HTML">&delta;(t)</span>. </div>','9','10','5');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7269,'math',NULL,'|\\alpha|<1',9,10,6);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7270,'math',NULL,'|\\alpha|\\geq 1',9,10,6);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7271,'paragraph',NULL,'Throughout our discussion, we have repeatedly mentioned the condition <span class="ITS_HTML">|&alpha;|<1</span>.  In this case, the inverse filter  consists of an infinite set of impulses whose sizes decrease exponentially. If <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?|\\alpha|\\geq 1"/> the sizes of the impulses in the inverse filter impulse response would not decrease. Such a system would be an unstable system and would not be useful in practice. In many situations, however, inverse filters can be derived to at least partially compensate for echoes or other linear distortions. Another notable example is in data communication where adaptive inverse filters are used to compensate for the transmission channel.','9','10','6');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7272,'section',NULL,'Summary',9,11,1);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7273,'section',NULL,'Summary',9,11,1);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7274,'paragraph',NULL,'<h3 class="ITS_BOOK">9-10  Summary</h3>','9','11','1');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7275,'paragraph',NULL,'In this chapter, we have turned our attention to continuous-time signals and systems.  We have shown that, just as in the case of discrete-time signals, linear time-invariant continuous-time systems are completely characterized by their response to a unit impulse signal, in the sense that for any given input to the LTI system, the output can be computed as the continuous-time convolution of the input and the impulse response. We showed how to evaluate convolutions of impulses with other signals including other impulse signals, and we gave several examples that illustrate how to evaluate convolution integrals involving piecewise constant or piecewise exponential signals.  We also showed that the properties of convolution allow us to manipulate cascade or parallel combinations of LTI systems, and we found that the causality and stability of an LTI system can be tested easily by examining the impulse response.  In conclusion, we showed a simple example of how the concept of convolution can be used to represent a practical signal processing problem.','9','11','2');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7276,'paragraph',NULL,'This chapter contains two demos:','9','11','5');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7277,'paragraph',NULL,'<ol class="ITS_alph"> <li> The <tt>dconvdemo</tt>  demonstrates discrete-time convolution.\\ <h3 class="ITS_NOTE"><b>DEMO:</b> Discrete Convolution</h3> <li> The <tt>cconvdemo</tt> demonstrates continuous-time convolution.\\ <h3 class="ITS_NOTE"><b>DEMO:</b> Continuous Convolution</h3> </ol> Both are MATLAB  graphical user interfaces (GUIs) that help students visualize the process of convolution.  Some features are; 1) Users can choose from a variety of signals; 2) Signals can be dragged around with the mouse and the display is updated in real-time; 3) Tutorial mode allows the student to hide the convolution; 4) Various plot options make both GUIs effective in a lecture/classroom environment. Lab #12 provides a structured framework for students to use both convolution GUIs.\\ <h3 class="ITS_NOTE"><b>LAB:</b> #12 Two Convolution GUIs</h3>','9','11','6');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7278,'paragraph',NULL,'The reader is again reminded of the large number of solved homework problems on the CD-ROM that are available for review and practice.\\ <h3 class="ITS_NOTE"><b>NOTE:</b> Hundreds of Solved Problems</h3>','9','11','7');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7279,'chapter',NULL,'Frequency Response',10,1,1);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7280,'chapter',NULL,'Frequency Response',10,1,1);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7281,'paragraph',NULL,'<h2 class="ITS_BOOK">CHAPTER 10<p>Frequency Response</h2>','10','1','1');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7282,'math',NULL,'\\delta(t)',10,1,3);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7283,'math',NULL,'u(t)',10,1,3);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7284,'paragraph',NULL,'In Chapter <a href="chapt:cont_time_signals" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> we showed that the operation of continuous-time convolution is synonymous with the definition of a continuous-time LTI system. The convolution integral is easy to apply as an analysis tool when the input signal is an impulse, <span class="ITS_HTML">&delta;(t)</span>, a step <span class="ITS_HTML">u(t)</span>, or combinations of piecewise exponential signals. However, we know from experience with digital filters (as in Chapter <a href="chapter:six-FIR-freq" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>) that the <i> frequency response function</i> is a very efficient way to characterize an LTI system for sinusoidal inputs, so we now set out to do that same characterization for analog filters (i.e., continuous-time systems).  We will start with the case where the input signal is a single sinusoid, but then we will show that the same viewpoint and methods apply when the input signal is any periodic waveform.','10','1','3');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7285,'section',NULL,'The Frequency Response Function for LTI Systems',10,2,1);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7286,'section',NULL,'The Frequency Response Function for LTI Systems',10,2,1);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7287,'paragraph',NULL,'<h3 class="ITS_BOOK">10-1  The Frequency Response Function for LTI Systems</h3>','10','2','1');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7288,'equation','eq:CT-convolution','y(t) = h(t) \\ast x(t) = \\int\\limits_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} h(\\tau) x(t-\\tau) \\,d\\tau',10,2,2);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7289,'math',NULL,'y(t)',10,2,2);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7290,'math',NULL,'x(t)',10,2,2);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7291,'math',NULL,'h(t)',10,2,2);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7292,'math',NULL,'\\delta(t)',10,2,2);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7293,'paragraph',NULL,'We want to develop a simple formula for the <i> sinusoidal response</i> of an LTI system. The general description of  LTI systems tells us that the general output <span class="ITS_HTML">y(t)</span> is obtained from the general input <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> by the convolution operation defined as <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?y(t) = h(t) \\ast x(t) = \\int\\limits_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} h(\\tau) x(t-\\tau) \\,d\\tau"/></div> where the impulse response <span class="ITS_HTML">h(t)</span> is the output when the input is the unit-impulse signal <span class="ITS_HTML">&delta;(t)</span>.','10','2','2');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7294,'equation','eq:eigen-property','\\begin{align} y(t) &= h(t) \\ast x(t)\\nonumber\\\\ &= \\int\\limits_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} h(\\tau) A e^{j\\phi} e^{j\\omega  (t- \\tau)} \\,d\\tau \\nonumber\\\\ &= \\int\\limits_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} h(\\tau) A e^{j\\phi} e^{j\\omega  t} e^{-j\\omega \\tau} \\,d\\tau \\nonumber\\\\ &=  \\left ( \\;  \\int\\limits_{-\\infty^{\\infty} h(\\tau) e^{-j\\omega \\tau } \\,d\\tau \\right )} A e^{j\\phi} e^{j\\omega  t} \\nonumber\\\\ &=  H(j\\omega) Ae^{j\\phi}e^{j\\omega t}  \\end{align}',10,2,3);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7295,'equation','eq:CT-complex-exp','x(t) = A e^{j\\phi} e^{j\\omega t} \\quad    -\\infty\\;<\\;t\\;<\\;\\infty',10,2,3);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7296,'math',NULL,'\\omega',10,2,3);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7297,'paragraph',NULL,'Rather than tackle the sinusoidal case directly, we take the input signal to be  a complex exponential   of the form <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(t) = A e^{j\\phi} e^{j\\omega t} \\quad    -\\infty\\;<\\;t\\;<\\;\\infty"/></div> We will show that the corresponding output signal is another complex exponential <i> at the same frequency.</i> We know that this is true for discrete-time LTI systems.  To prove that this is also true for continuous-time LTI systems, we can substitute <a href="eq:CT-complex-exp" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> into the convolution integral <a href="eq:CT-convolution" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> and employ the laws of exponents to simplify the expression as follows: <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} y(t) &= h(t) \\ast x(t)\\nonumber\\\\ &= \\int\\limits_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} h(\\tau) A e^{j\\phi} e^{j\\omega  (t- \\tau)} \\,d\\tau \\nonumber\\\\ &= \\int\\limits_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} h(\\tau) A e^{j\\phi} e^{j\\omega  t} e^{-j\\omega \\tau} \\,d\\tau \\nonumber\\\\ &=  \\left ( \\;  \\int\\limits_{-\\infty^{\\infty} h(\\tau) e^{-j\\omega \\tau } \\,d\\tau \\right )} A e^{j\\phi} e^{j\\omega  t} \\nonumber\\\\ &=  H(j\\omega) Ae^{j\\phi}e^{j\\omega t}  \\end{align}"/></div> The integral within the parentheses reduces to a complex constant when the frequency <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span> is given a specific value. This  complex quantity tells us how the system changes the magnitude and phase of the input signal as it forms the output signal.','10','2','3');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7298,'equation','none',' y(t) =(2\\sqrt{2}e^{-j\\pi/4})10 e^{j3\\pi t} = 20\\sqrt{2} e^{j(3\\pi t-\\pi/4)} ',10,2,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7299,'math',NULL,' x(t) = 10 e^{j3\\pi t}',10,2,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7300,'math',NULL,'H(j3\\pi)',10,2,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7301,'math',NULL,'2-j2',10,2,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7302,'math',NULL,'y(t) = B e^{j\\theta}e^{j3\\pi t}',10,2,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7303,'math',NULL,'H(j3\\pi)',10,2,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7304,'math',NULL,'20\\sqrt{2}',10,2,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7305,'math',NULL,'-\\pi/4',10,2,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7306,'paragraph',NULL,'<div class="ITS_EXAMPLE"><span class="ITS_EXAMPLE_TITLE">EXAMPLE: Complex-Exponential Output</span><p>% Suppose that the input to an LTI system is <span class="ITS_HTML"> x(t) = 10 e<sup>j3&pi; t</sup></span>, and the value of <span class="ITS_HTML">H(j3&pi;)</span>   is <span class="ITS_HTML">2-j2</span>. The output can be expressed as <span class="ITS_HTML">y(t) = B e<sup>j&theta;</sup>e<sup>j3&pi; t</sup></span> if we convert <span class="ITS_HTML">H(j3&pi;)</span> to polar form and multiply. <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? y(t) =(2\\sqrt{2}e^{-j\\pi/4})10 e^{j3\\pi t} = 20\\sqrt{2} e^{j(3\\pi t-\\pi/4)} "/></div> Thus the output complex exponential has a magnitude of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?20\\sqrt{2}"/> and a phase of <span class="ITS_HTML">-&pi;/4</span>. </div>','10','2','4');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7307,'equation','eq:define-frequency-response',' \\begin{array}{c} \\mbox{ {Frequency Response of an LTI System}} \\\\ {  H(j\\omega) =  \\int\\limits_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} h(t) e^{-j\\omega t} \\,dt} \\end{array} ',10,2,5);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7308,'math',NULL,'\\omega',10,2,5);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7309,'math',NULL,'H(j\\omega)',10,2,5);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7310,'math',NULL,'\\omega',10,2,5);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7311,'math',NULL,'\\omega',10,2,5);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7312,'paragraph',NULL,'According to <a href="eq:eigen-property" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, when the input is a complex exponential signal whose frequency is <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span>, the output is also a complex-exponential signal having exactly the same frequency. However, the effect of the system on a complex-exponential signal  depends on the frequency of the input. This is represented by the fact that we will get different complex values for <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?H(j\\omega)"/> as <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span> changes. If we let the frequency vary, we can define the <font color="blue">frequency response</font> of a continuous-time system as the following function of <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span>: <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="eqbox" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? \\begin{array}{c} \ {Frequency Response of an LTI System} \\\\ {  H(j\\omega) =  \\int\\limits_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} h(t) e^{-j\\omega t} \\,dt} \\end{array} "/></div>','10','2','5');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7313,'math',NULL,'\\tau',10,2,6);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7314,'math',NULL,'t',10,2,6);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7315,'math',NULL,'t',10,2,6);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7316,'math',NULL,'t',10,2,6);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7317,'footnote',NULL,'It is common practice to do this even though we normally reserve <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span> for the independent variable of a signal. Usually this causes no problem, but be careful not to use <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span> in two different ways in the same equation.',10,2,6);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7318,'paragraph',NULL,'\iffalse Note that we have changed the dummy variable of integration from <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tau"/> to <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span>. <sup><a href="#" class="ITS_footnote">[note]</a></sup>\fi','10','2','6');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7319,'equation','eq:filter_example','\\begin{align} H(j\\omega) &=   \\int\\limits_{0}^{\\infty} 2e^{-2t-j\\omega t}   \\,dt \\nonumber \\\\ &=  \\left . \\frac{2e^{-2t-j\\omega t}}{-2-j\\omega} \\; \\right |_{0}^{\\infty} = 0 -  \\frac{2}{-2-j\\omega}  \\nonumber \\\\ &=  \\frac{2}{2 + j\\omega}  \\end{align}',10,2,8);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7320,'equation','none',' H(j\\omega) = \\int\\limits_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} 2e^{-2t} u(t)  e^{-j\\omega t } \\,dt ',10,2,8);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7321,'math',NULL,'H(j\\omega)',10,2,8);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7322,'math',NULL,'\\omega',10,2,8);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7323,'math',NULL,'H(j\\omega)',10,2,8);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7324,'math',NULL,'H(j\\omega)',10,2,8);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7325,'math',NULL,'h(t) = 2e^{-2t} u(t)',10,2,8);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7326,'math',NULL,'t=\\infty',10,2,8);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7327,'math',NULL,'\\lim_{t\\to\\infty}|e^{-2t-j\\omega t}|=e^{-2t}\\to 0',10,2,8);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7328,'paragraph',NULL,'In general, we want the functional form of <span class="ITS_HTML">H(j&omega;)</span> so that we can plot <a href="eq:define-frequency-response" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> versus the frequency variable <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span>, and see the effect of the system on <i> any</i> complex-exponential input signal.  That is, we need to evaluate the integral in <a href="eq:define-frequency-response" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> to obtain an expression for <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?H(j\\omega)"/> in terms of familiar mathematical functions.  The following example illustrates this for a real one-sided exponential impulse response. <div class="ITS_EXAMPLE"><span class="ITS_EXAMPLE_TITLE">EXAMPLE: Formula for <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?H(j\\omega)"/></span><p>%Suppose that the impulse response is <span class="ITS_HTML">h(t) = 2e<sup>-2t</sup> u(t)</span>. We can determine a formula for the frequency response of the LTI system by evaluating the following integral: <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? H(j\\omega) = \\int\\limits_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} 2e^{-2t} u(t)  e^{-j\\omega t } \\,dt "/></div> The steps are <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} H(j\\omega) &=   \\int\\limits_{0}^{\\infty} 2e^{-2t-j\\omega t}   \\,dt \\nonumber \\\\ &=  \\left . \\frac{2e^{-2t-j\\omega t}}{-2-j\\omega} \\; \\right |_{0}^{\\infty} = 0 -  \\frac{2}{-2-j\\omega}  \\nonumber \\\\ &=  \\frac{2}{2 + j\\omega}  \\end{align}"/></div> The evaluation at the upper limit <span class="ITS_HTML">t=&infin;</span> is zero because <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\lim_{t\\to\\infty}|e^{-2t-j\\omega t}|=e^{-2t}\\to 0"/>. </div>','10','2','8');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7329,'math',NULL,'H(j\\omega)',10,2,10);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7330,'math',NULL,'\\omega',10,2,10);
