INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7356,'subsubsection',NULL,'Logarithmic Plot',10,2,12);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7357,'subsubsection',NULL,'Logarithmic Plot',10,2,12);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7358,'paragraph',NULL,'<h3 class="ITS_BOOK">10-0.3.1  Logarithmic Plot</h3> In MATLAB  we can use <tt>freqs()</tt> to do a complete evaluation over a dense grid and make a plot. Since the frequency axis is infinitely long, it is common to use a logarithmic spacing along the horizontal axis to cover several decades (factors of 10) in frequency. Figure <a href="fig:HW-1st-order" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(a) shows such a plot for the frequency response function of this example. \figurepsAlt{Chapter10/art/HW-1st-order5in}{Chapter10/art/Hw-1st-order} {(a) MATLAB  plot of frequency response of a first-order analog filter, created by the function <tt>[H,W]=freqs(2,[1,2],logspace(-2,2,401))</tt>. The frequency axis is logarithmic. (b) Loglog plot of the frequency response. } The points <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega; = 2</span> and <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega; = 20</span> are marked on the graph. Notice that only the positive-frequency part of the magnitude of the frequency response is plotted in Fig. <a href="fig:HW-1st-order" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>. This is because the frequency response magnitude for <a href="eq:filter_example_mag" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> is even, i.e., <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?|H(-j\\omega)|=|H(j\\omega) |"/>. In the general case of a system with real impulse response, we will show that <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?H(-j\\omega)=\\Hcoma"/>, where <span class="ITS_HTML"><sup>*</sup></span> denotes complex conjugation. Therefore,  the magnitude is an even function of <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span>, <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?|H(-j\\omega)|=|\\Hcoma|=|H(j\\omega) |"/>, and we do not need to explicitly plot the entire frequency axis.','10','2','12');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7359,'math',NULL,'\\omega=2',10,2,13);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7360,'paragraph',NULL,'Figure <a href="fig:HW-1st-order" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(b) shows the same frequency response, but this time a log scale is used for both magnitude and frequency.  Notice that in this case the frequency response appears to fall off linearly with frequency above <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;=2</span> rad/sec.  The curve drops by a multiplicative factor of 0.1 for each factor of 10 increase in frequency.  This feature of loglog frequency response plots is very useful for higher-order continuous-time systems where the falloff is linear but faster on a loglog plot. Plots of this type are called &ldquo;Bode plots&rdquo;.','10','2','13');
