INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7893,'subsection',NULL,'Right-Sided Real Exponential Signals',11,5,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7894,'subsection',NULL,'Right-Sided Real Exponential Signals',11,5,4);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7895,'paragraph',NULL,'<h3 class="ITS_BOOK">11-3.1  Right-Sided Real Exponential Signals</h3> The signal <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t) = e<sup>-at</sup>u(t)</span>  is called a <i> right-sided exponential signal</i> because it is nonzero only on the right side of its graph as shown in Figure <a href="fig:right_exp" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(a).  In Example <a href="ex:exp_sig" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> we did a specific case <span class="ITS_HTML">(a=7)</span> of the following Fourier transform pair: <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="eqbox" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? \\begin{array}{ccc} \\BlackTD && \\OrangeFD\\\\ e^{-at}u(t) & \\Fgoes & \\OrangeFT { \\frac{1}{a+j\\omega}}  \\\\ \\end{array} "/></div> The absolute integrability condition of <a href="eq:abs_integrable" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> shows that <span class="ITS_HTML">a</span> must be positive in order to have a legitimate transform pair in <a href="eq:exp_sig_pair-2" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>. If we substitute the function <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)=e<sup>-at</sup> u(t)</span> into <a href="eq:abs_integrable" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> we obtain <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align*} \\int_0^{\\infty} |e^{-at}|dt &= \\int_0^{\\infty} e^{-at} dt = -\\left.\\frac{1}{a}\\,  e^{-at}\\right|_0^{\\infty} \\end{align*}"/></div> This result will be finite only if <span class="ITS_HTML">e<sup>-at</sup></span> at the upper limit of <span class="ITS_HTML">&infin;</span> is bounded, which is true  only if  <span class="ITS_HTML">a>0</span>. Thus, the right-sided exponential signal is guaranteed to have a Fourier transform if it dies out with increasing <span class="ITS_HTML">t</span>, which requires <span class="ITS_HTML">a>0</span>.  Otherwise, if <span class="ITS_HTML">a&le; 0</span>, the right-sided exponential either does not die out or it increases without bound and, therefore,  does not have a Fourier transform when <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?a\\leq0"/>.','11','5','4');
