INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(7975,'paragraph',NULL,'Several important properties of the sinc function are evident in Fig. <a href="fig:pulseFT" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(b): <ol class="ITS_enum"> <li> The value at <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega; = 0</span> is <span class="ITS_HTML">X(j0) = T</span>. When  we attempt to evaluate the sinc formula <a href="eq:pulse_trans" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> at <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;=0</span>, we obtain the indeterminate form <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\frac{0}{0}"/>. However, using L&lsquo;H\^{o}pital&lsquo;s rule from calculus, we obtain <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align*} X(j0) &= \\lim_{\\omega\\to 0} \\left( \\frac{\\sin(\\omega \\Tph)}{\\omega/2} \\right)\\\\ &= \\lim_{\\omega\\to 0}\\left( \\frac{ \\Tph \\cos(\\omega \\Tph)}{1/2}\\right)=  \\Tp \\end{align*}"/></div> Note that we could also use the small angle approximation for the sine function <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?(\\sin\\theta \\approx \\theta)"/> to obtain the same result  since <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? \\lim_{\\omega\\to 0} \\left( \\frac{\\sin(\\omega \\Tph)}{\\omega/2} \\right) \\approx \\frac{(\\omega \\Tph)}{\\omega/2}  = \\Tp "/></div> <li> The zeros of the sinc function are at nonzero integer multiples of <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega; = 2&pi;/T</span>, where <span class="ITS_HTML">T</span> is the total duration of the pulse. Notice that the sinc function oscillates between positive and negative values. Specifically, it crosses zero at regular intervals because we have the function <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\sin(\\omega \\Tph)"/> in the numerator. The zeros of the sinc function <a href="eq:pulse_trans" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> are the values of <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span> where the numerator of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)"/> becomes zero. These are the values of <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span> such that <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\sin(\\omega \\Tph)=0"/>. Since <span class="ITS_HTML">sin(&theta;)= 0</span> for <span class="ITS_HTML">&theta;=n&pi;</span> where <span class="ITS_HTML">n</span> is an integer, it follows that <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)=0"/> for <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\omega \\Tph=n\\pi"/> or <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\omega= (2\\pi/\\Tp)n"/>, as is shown in Figure <a href="fig:pulseFT" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>. \iffalse One way to remember this fact is to realize that the zero crossings are at nonzero integer multiples of <span class="ITS_HTML">2&pi;</span> over the length of the pulse <span class="ITS_HTML">(T)</span>. \fi <li> Because of the <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span> in the denominator of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)"/>, the function &ldquo;dies out&rdquo; with increasing <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span>, but only as fast as <span class="ITS_HTML">1/&omega;</span>. <li> <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)"/> is an even function, i.e., <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)=\\Xmoma"/>. <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? \\hspace{-1em} \\Xmoma = \\frac{\\sin(-\\omega T/2)}{-\\omega/2} = \\frac{-\\sin(\\omega T/2)}{-\\omega/2} = X(j\\omega) "/></div> Thus the real even-symmetric rectangular pulse has a real even-symmetric Fourier transform. </ol> These properties of the sinc function will be exploited in a variety of applications of the Fourier transform.','11','5','17');
