INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(8194,'math',NULL,'X(j\\omega)',11,6,12);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(8195,'paragraph',NULL,'In order to exhibit the various symmetries of the Fourier transform and their correspondence to symmetries of the time-domain signal,  we examine the impact of the flip and conjugate operators on  the real and imaginary parts of the Fourier transform of a real signal.  If we take the complex conjugate of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\Xmoma"/>, we obtain <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? X^*(-j\\omega) = \\left(\\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} x(t) e^{-(-j\\omega ) t}dt\\right)^* =\\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} x^*(t) e^{-j\\omega t}dt "/></div> That is, <span class="ITS_HTML">X<sup>*</sup>(-j&omega;)</span> is the Fourier transform of <span class="ITS_HTML"> x<sup>*</sup>(t)</span>. Therefore the following property is true for any <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span>: <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="eqbox" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? \\begin{array}{ccc} \\BlackTD && \\OrangeFD\\\\ x^*(t)  & \\Fgoes & \\OrangeFT  X^*(-j\\omega)  \\\\ \\end{array} "/></div> We can use <a href="eq:conjugate_pair" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> to derive many interesting symmetries for real signals.  If <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> is real, then <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t) = x<sup>*</sup>(t)</span> and, therefore, after taking the Fourier transform it must be true that <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)=X^*(-j\\omega)"/> or equivalently, for the real and imaginary parts we have: <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} \\mathb{R}\\{X(j\\omega)\\} &= \\mathb{R}\\{X^*(-j\\omega) \\}  \\\\ \I\\{X(j\\omega)\\} &= \I\\{X^*(-j\\omega) \\}  \\end{align}"/></div> Finally, we get the properties that apply  when <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> is real, <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} \\mathb{R}\\{X(j\\omega)\\} &= \\mathb{R}\\{\\Xmoma\\}  \\\\ \I\\{X(j\\omega)\\} &= -\I\\{\\Xmoma\\}  \\end{align}"/></div> In other words, when <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> is real, the real part of its Fourier transform is an <i> even</i> function of <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span> and the imaginary part is an <i> odd</i> function of <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span>.  These symmetries are evident in Figs. <a href="fig:right_exp" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(b) and <a href="fig:right_exp" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(c) on p. <a href="fig:right_exp" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>. The condition <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X^*(-j\\omega)=X(j\\omega)"/> also implies that the polar form representation <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)=|X(j\\omega)|e^{j\\angle X(j\\omega)}"/> has the following symmetries (see Problem <a href="prob:mag-phase-symmetries" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>): <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} |X(j\\omega)| &= |\\Xmoma|  \\\\ \\angle X(j\\omega) &= -\\angle \\Xmoma  \\end{align}"/></div> In other words, the magnitude has even symmetry and the phase angle has odd symmetry if <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> is real. <div class="ITS_EXAMPLE"><span class="ITS_EXAMPLE_TITLE">EXAMPLE: Magnitude/Phase Symmetries</span><p>% As another illustration of symmetry, recall that the Fourier transform of <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)=e<sup>-at</sup>u(t)</span> is <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? X(j\\omega) =\\frac{1}{a+j\\omega} "/></div> The magnitude is the square root of the magnitude-squared and the phase is extracted via the arctangent <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align*} |X(j\\omega)| & =  [X(j\\omega)\\Xcoma]^{1/2}\\\\ &= \\frac{1}{(a^2+\\omega^2)^{1/2}} = |X(-j\\omega)| \\\\ \\angle X(j\\omega) & =  -\\arctan \\left(\\frac{\\omega}{a}\\right) = -\\angle X(-j\\omega) \\end{align*}"/></div> The even and odd symmetries of the magnitude and phase given in the above equations are illustrated in the plots in Fig. <a href="fig:right_exp_mag" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>. In this case it would have been sufficient to plot the magnitude and phase for <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\omega\\geq0"/>. </div> <div class="ITS_Image"><center><img src="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch11/Fig11-11_FT_1st_order.png" alt="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch11/Fig11-11_FT_1st_order.png"></center><br><div class="ITS_Caption">Magnitude and phase angle of Fourier transform of right-sided exponential signal: (a) Magnitude of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)"/> is even; (b) Phase angle of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)"/> is odd.</span></div></div>','11','6','12');
