INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(9169,'paragraph',NULL,'<h3 class="ITS_BOOK">12-2.3  Bandlimited Signal Reconstruction</h3>  To see how a bandlimited signal can be reconstructed from its samples, we return to Fig. <a href="fig:samp_reconst" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, which shows the signal being reconstructed by an LTI lowpass  filter  with frequency response <span class="ITS_HTML">H<sub>r</sub>(j&omega;)</span> <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align}  X_r(j\\omega) &= H_r(j\\omega)X_s(j\\omega)\\\\ &= H_r(j\\omega)\\frac{1}{T_s} \\sum_{k=-\\infty}^{\\infty} X(j(\\omega-k\\omega_s)) \\nonumber \\end{align}"/></div> The individual Fourier transforms in <a href="eq:FT-for-reconsctruction" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> are illustrated in Fig. <a href="fig:reconst_trans" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, where it is assumed that the sampling rate is high enough to avoid aliasing distortion. If  the frequency response of the filter is ideal <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?H_r(j\\omega) =  \\begin{cases} T_s & \\quad  |\\omega|\\leq \\omega_s/2 = \\pi/T_s \\\\ 0 & \\quad  |\\omega|> \\omega_s/2 = \\pi/T_s \\end{cases}"/></div> \NullOrange as depicted  in Fig. <a href="fig:reconst_trans" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(b),  the filter will extract <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)"/> from the sum of shifted copies in Fig. <a href="fig:reconst_trans" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(a) and give the final result <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X_r(j\\omega)= X(j\\omega)"/> in Fig. <a href="fig:reconst_trans" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(c). Therefore, when the input signal is bandlimited and the sampling rate is at least twice the highest frequency of the input signal, then the reconstruction is perfect and we have <span class="ITS_HTML">x<sub>r</sub>(t)=x<sub>s</sub>(t)*h<sub>r</sub>(t) = x(t)</span>. \figurepsAlt {Chapter12/art/reconst_trans5in}{Chapter12/art/reconstruct_trans} {Illustration of frequency-domain representation of reconstruction from sampled signal: (a) Fourier transform of sampled signal <span class="ITS_HTML">x<sub>s</sub>(t)</span>. (b) Ideal reconstruction filter. (c) Fourier transform of output of ideal bandlimited reconstruction filter.   } <div class="ITS_EXAMPLE"><span class="ITS_EXAMPLE_TITLE">EXAMPLE: Spectrum during Sampling</span><p>%As an example of sampling and reconstruction of a bandlimited signal, consider <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? x(t) = \\frac{1}{3\\pi} + \\frac{1}{3\\pi}\\cos(\\pi t + \\pi/2) "/></div> whose Fourier transform is <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? X(j\\omega)  = \\frac{2}{3} \\delta(\\omega) + \\frac{j}{3} \\delta(\\omega - \\pi) -\\frac{j}{3} \\delta(\\omega + \\pi) "/></div> The highest frequency in this signal is <span class="ITS_HTML">&pi;</span> rad/sec, so any sampling rate such that <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;<sub>s</sub>=2&pi;/T<sub>s</sub> > 2&pi;</span> will guarantee that we can exactly reconstruct the signal <span class="ITS_HTML">x(t)</span> from its samples <span class="ITS_HTML">x[n]=x(nT<sub>s</sub>)</span>. Figure <a href="fig:samp_example" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(a) shows <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)"/> and Fig. <a href="fig:samp_example" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(b) shows <span class="ITS_HTML">X<sub>s</sub>(j&omega;)</span> for <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;<sub>s</sub> = 6&pi;</span>, or <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?T_s = \\frac{1 sec. <div class="ITS_Image"><center><img src="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch12/Fig12-17_samp_example.png" alt="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch12/Fig12-17_samp_example.png"></center><br><div class="ITS_Caption">Illustration of frequency-domain representation of sampling: (a) Fourier transform of signal <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x(t)=\\frac{1}{3\\pi}+\\frac{1}{3\\pi}\\cos(\\pi t + \\pi/2)"/>; (b) Fourier transform of sampled signal <span class="ITS_HTML">x<sub>s</sub>(t)</span>. Light colored box is the ideal reconstruction filter with cutoff frequency at <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega; = 3&pi;</span>.</span></div></div> The light colored  box in Fig. <a href="fig:samp_example" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(b) is the frequency response of the ideal reconstruction filter <span class="ITS_HTML">H<sub>r</sub>(j&omega;)</span> for a sampling rate of <span class="ITS_HTML">6&pi;</span> rad/s; in other words, its cutoff frequency is <span class="ITS_HTML">3&pi;</span> rad/s. Note that the product of <span class="ITS_HTML">X<sub>r</sub>(j&omega;)=H<sub>r</sub>(j&omega;)X<sub>s</sub>(j&omega;)</span> will be exactly equal to the original  Fourier transform <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?X(j\\omega)"/> as expected. Therefore, the output of the ideal reconstruction filter in Fig. <a href="fig:samp_example" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> will be <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? x_r(t)= x(t) = \\frac{1}{3\\pi} + \\frac{1}{3\\pi}\\cos(\\pi t + \\pi/2) "/></div> </div>','12','4','10');
