INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(9190,'paragraph',NULL,'<h3 class="ITS_BOOK">12-2.5  Bandlimited Interpolation</h3> Figure <a href="fig:reconst_filter" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(a) shows the impulse response <a href="eq:ideal_reconst_imp_resp" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> of the ideal reconstruction filter. The corresponding frequency response <a href="eq:reconst_filter_trans" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> is shown in Fig. <a href="fig:reconst_filter" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(b). <div class="ITS_Image"><center><img src="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch12/Fig12-18_ideal_BL_Recon_Filter.png" alt="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch12/Fig12-18_ideal_BL_Recon_Filter.png"></center><br><div class="ITS_Caption">Ideal bandlimited reconstruction filter: (a) Impulse response <span class="ITS_HTML">h<sub>r</sub>(t)</span>; (b) Frequency response <span class="ITS_HTML">H<sub>r</sub>(j&omega;)</span>.</span></div></div> <div class="ITS_Image"><center><img src="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch12/Fig12-19_ideal_BL_Recon_Filter.png" alt="FILES/SP1Figures/Ch12/Fig12-19_ideal_BL_Recon_Filter.png"></center><br><div class="ITS_Caption">Illustration of time-domain  reconstructed signal as the sum of the individual weighted and shifted sinc functions.</span></div></div> Note that the ideal lowpass reconstruction filter has gain <span class="ITS_HTML">T<sub>s</sub></span> and cutoff frequency <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\omega_\ co=\\omega_s/2 =\\pi/T_s"/>.  The impulse response, which is <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?h_r(t) = \\frac{\\sin\\frac{\\pi}{T_s}t}{\\frac{\\pi}{T_s}t}"/></div> has a maximum value of 1 at <span class="ITS_HTML">t=0</span> and it is zero at nonzero integer multiples of <span class="ITS_HTML">T<sub>s</sub></span>  in Fig. <a href="fig:reconst_filter" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>(a). The time-domain expression for the output of the reconstruction filter is obtained by substituting <a href="eq:mod_imp_train-2" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> on p. <a href="eq:mod_imp_train-2" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> for <span class="ITS_HTML">x<sub>s</sub>(t)</span> into <div class="ITS_EQUATION"> x<sub>r</sub>(t)= x<sub>s</sub>(t)*h<sub>r</sub>(t) </div> This substitution leads to <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} x_r(t) &= x_s(t)*h_r(t) \\nonumber \\\\ &=\\left(\\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty} x(nT_s) \\delta(t-nT_s)\\right)*h_r(t) \\nonumber \\\\ &=  \\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty} x(nT_s) h_r(t-nT_s)  \\end{align}"/></div> That is,  the continuous-time reconstructed signal <span class="ITS_HTML">x<sub>r</sub>(t)</span> consists of an infinite sum of scaled and shifted impulse responses of the reconstruction filter, as discussed previously in Section <a href="sec:DC-conversion" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> in Chapter <a href="chapter:four-sampling" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>. When <a href="eq:ideal_reconst_imp_resp" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> is substituted into <a href="eq:interp_formula" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, we obtain the following result: <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="eqbox" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? \\begin{array}{c} \{  A bandlimited signal x(t) }\\\\ \{ such that X(j\\omega) =0 for |\\omega|\\geq \\omega_b}\\\\ \{ can be reconstructed exactly from}\\\\ \{ samples taken with sampling}\\\\ \{  rate \\omega_s=2\\pi/T_s \\geq 2\\omega_b via } \\\\ \{ the bandlimited interpolation formula:}\\\\ {  x_r(t) =\\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty} x(nT_s)\\frac{\\sin\\left[\\frac{\\pi}{T_s}\\left(t-nT_s\\right)\\right]} {\\frac{\\pi}{T_s}\\left(t-nT_s\\right)}} \\end{array} "/></div>','12','4','12');
