INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(9307,'paragraph',NULL,'Recall from Chapters <a href="chapter:seven-z-transform" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> and <a href="chapter:eight-IIR" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> that the discrete-time system can be described by the <span class="ITS_HTML">z</span>-transform relation <div class="ITS_EQUATION">Y(z)=H(z)X(z)</div> or equivalently, by the DTFT relation <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?Y(e^{j\\om})=H(e^{j\\om})X(e^{j\\om})"/></div> The output of the D-to-C converter is given by the time-domain relation <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?y(t) = \\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty}  y[n]h_r(t-nT_s)"/></div> where <span class="ITS_HTML">h<sub>r</sub>(t)</span> is given by <a href="eq:ideal_reconst_imp_resp" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> on p. <a href="eq:ideal_reconst_imp_resp" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>.  Now the frequency-domain representation of the D-to-C converter is easily derived by taking the <i> continuous-time</i> Fourier transform of <a href="eq:d-to-c-output" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, obtaining <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} Y(j\\omega)  &=  \\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty} y[n] H_r(j\\omega) e^{-j\\omega n T_s } \\nonumber \\\\ &=   H_r(j\\omega) \\sum_{n=-\\infty}^{\\infty} y[n]  e^{-j\\omega T_s n}\\nonumber \\\\ &=  H_r(j\\omega) Y(e^{j\\omega T_s})  \\end{align}"/></div> If we substitute <a href="eq:LTI-DTFT" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> and <a href="eq:DTFT-2" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> into <a href="eq:d-to-c-output_trans" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, we obtain <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} Y(j\\omega)  &= H_r(j\\omega) H(e^{j\\omega T_s}) X(e^{j\\omega T_s}) \\nonumber \\\\ & = H_r(j\\omega) H(e^{j\\omega T_s})\\frac{1}{T_s} \\sum_{k=-\\infty}^{\\infty} X_c(j(\\omega-2\\pi k/T_s))  \\end{align}"/></div> While <a href="eq:output_trans" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> looks quite complex, it is not really too difficult to interpret.  First of all, the summation is a sum of shifted copies of <span class="ITS_HTML">X<sub>c</sub>(j&omega;)</span>.  By construction, that sum is necessarily periodic with period <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;<sub>s</sub>=2&pi;/T<sub>s</sub></span> in the variable <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;</span>. Furthermore, if <span class="ITS_HTML">X<sub>c</sub>(j&omega;) =0</span> for <span class="ITS_HTML">|&omega;|>&omega;<sub>b</sub></span> and <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;<sub>s</sub>>2&omega;<sub>b</sub></span>, then the shifted copies do not overlap, and one period of the function is exactly equal to <span class="ITS_HTML">(1/T<sub>s</sub>)X<sub>c</sub>(j&omega;) </span> in the frequency interval <span class="ITS_HTML">-&pi;/T<sub>s</sub> < &omega; < &pi;/T<sub>s</sub></span>. The middle term, <span class="ITS_HTML">H(e<sup>j&omega; T<sub>s</sub></sup>)</span>, is also periodic with period <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;<sub>s</sub>=2&pi;/T<sub>s</sub></span>.  The left-hand term, <span class="ITS_HTML">H<sub>r</sub>(j&omega;)</span> has a gain of <span class="ITS_HTML">T<sub>s</sub></span> and is zero outside the interval <span class="ITS_HTML">|&omega;| &le; &omega;<sub>s</sub>/2=&pi;/T<sub>s</sub></span>. Therefore, if no aliasing distortion occurs, the output Fourier transform is <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?Y(j\\omega)  =  \\begin{cases} H(e^{j\\omega T_s}) X_c(j\\omega)  & \\quad  |\\omega| \\leq \\pi/T_s \\\\ 0 & \\quad  \otherwise \\end{cases}"/></div>','12','4','27');
