INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(10466,'paragraph',NULL,'The DFT  <a href="eq:DFT-2" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a> has been introduced by showing that it results from computing the DTFT of a finite-length sequence at a finite set of frequencies. Equation <a href="eq:DFT-2" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>  can in fact be applied to <i> any</i> finite-length sequence whether it resulted from time-windowing a sampled signal or not.  Adding to the interest in the DFT is the fact that there exists an <i> inverse discrete Fourier transform</i> (or IDFT); i.e., a computation that converts <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tilde{X}[k]"/> for <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?k=0,1,\\ldots,\\Nmone"/> back into the sequence <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tilde{x}[n]"/> for <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?n=0,1,\\ldots,\\Nmone"/>.  The inverse DFT is <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="beq" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} \\tilde{x}[n] = \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{k=0}^{N-1} &\\tilde{X}[k] e^{j(2\\pi k/N) n}\\\\ &\\quad   0\\leq n \\leq \\Nmone \\end{align}"/></div> Equations  <a href="eq:IDFT" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>  and <a href="eq:DFT-2" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>  are a unique relationship between a sequence <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tilde{x}[n]"/> and its DFT <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tilde{X}[k]"/>. Following our earlier terminology for Fourier representations, the DFT defined by <a href="eq:DFT-2" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>  is the <i> analysis</i> equation and IDFT defined by <a href="eq:IDFT" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>  is the <i> synthesis</i> equation. To prove that these equations are a consistent Fourier representation, we note that <a href="eq:IDFT" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>, because it is a finite, well-defined computation, would surely produce <i> some</i> sequence when evaluated for <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?n=0,1,\\ldots,\\Nmone"/>. So let us call that sequence <span class="ITS_HTML">v[n]</span> until we prove otherwise. Part of the proof is given by the following steps: <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} v[n]&={\\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{k=0}^{N-1} \\tilde{X}[k] e^{j(2\\pi k/N) n}}\\nonumber\\\\ &= {\\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}\\left( \\sum_{m=0}^{N-1} \\tilde{x}[m] e^{-j(2\\pi k/N) m} \\right) e^{j(2\\pi k/N) n}}\\nonumber\\\\ &= { \\frac{1}{N} \\sum_{m=0}^{N-1} \\tilde{x}[m]\\left( \\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}e^{j(2\\pi k/N) (n-m)} \\right) }\\nonumber\\\\ &= \\tilde{x}[n]  \\end{align}"/></div> Several things happened in the manipulations leading up to the assertion of <a href="eq:IDFT-derivation" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>.   On the second line, we substituted the right-hand side of <a href="eq:DFT-2" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>  for <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\tilde{X}[k]"/> after changing the index of summation from <span class="ITS_HTML">n</span> to <span class="ITS_HTML">m</span>.  We are allowed to make this change because this is a &ldquo;dummy index&rdquo; that can have any label, and we need to keep <span class="ITS_HTML">n</span> reserved for the index of the sequence <span class="ITS_HTML">v[n]</span> that is synthesized by the IDFT.  On the third line, the summations on <span class="ITS_HTML">k</span> and <span class="ITS_HTML">m</span> were interchanged. This is permissable since these are finite sums and can be done in any order.  Now we need to consider the term in parenthesis in the third line of the proof. The following exercise states the result, which can be easily verified. <div class="ITS_EXE"><div class="ITS_EXE_logo">Exercise:</div> Use the formula <div class="ITS_EQUATION"><img class="bracket" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi? \\sum_{k=0}^{N-1} \\alpha^k = \\frac{1-\\alpha^N}{1-\\alpha} "/></div> to show that <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} { \\sum_{k=0}^{N-1}e^{j(2\\pi k/N) (n-m)}} &= { \\frac{1-e^{j(2\\pi) (n-m)}} {1-e^{j(2\\pi/N)(n-m)}}} \\nonumber \\\\ &=  \\begin{cases} N & \\quad  n-m=rN \\\\ 0 & \\quad  \otherwise \\end{cases}  \\end{align}"/></div> where <span class="ITS_HTML">r</span> is any positive or negative integer including <span class="ITS_HTML">r=0</span>. </div>','13','10','5');
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(10467,'math',NULL,'m',13,10,6);
