INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(10739,'math',NULL,'x[n]',13,12,1);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(10740,'section',NULL,'Spectrum Analysis of Periodic Signals',13,12,1);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(10741,'section',NULL,'Spectrum Analysis of Periodic Signals',13,12,1);
INSERT INTO dspfirst (id,meta,name,content,chapter,section,paragraph) VALUES(10742,'paragraph',NULL,'<h3 class="ITS_BOOK">13-11  Spectrum Analysis of Periodic Signals</h3>  In this section we will show how the DFT can be used to analyze periodic signals such as those that can be represented by a finite sum of harmonically related cosine signals. As a specific example, consider the periodic continuous-time signal <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} x_c(t) &= 0.0472 \\cos(2\\pi(200) t + 1.5077)\\nonumber\\\\ &\\quad   +0.1362 \\cos(2\\pi(400) t + 1.8769) \\nonumber\\\\ &\\quad   + 0.4884 \\cos(2\\pi(500) t -0.1852)\\nonumber\\\\ &\\quad   +  0.2942 \\cos(2 \\pi(1600) t -1.4488) \\nonumber\\\\ &\\quad    +0.1223 \\cos(2\\pi(1700) t)  \\end{align}"/></div> The fundamental frequency of this signal is <span class="ITS_HTML">&omega;<sub>0</sub>=2&pi;(100)</span> rad/sec, and the signal consists of harmonics at 2, 4, 5, 16, and 17 times the fundamental.  This signal is quite similar to the synthetic vowel studied in Section <a href="sec:Vowel-Demo" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>. If we sample this signal with sampling rate <span class="ITS_HTML">f<sub>s</sub>=4000</span> Hz, the resulting discrete-time signal will be periodic too, since 100 divides evenly into 4000. Specifically, the discrete-time signal <span class="ITS_HTML">x[n]=x<sub>c</sub>(n/4000)</span> given by <div class="ITS_EQUATION2"><img class="ITS_EQUATION" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\begin{align} x[n] &= 0.0472 \\cos(0.1\\pi n + 1.5077)\\nonumber \\\\ &\\quad    +0.1362 \\cos(0.2\\pi n + 1.8769) \\nonumber\\\\ &\\quad    +0.4884 \\cos(0.25\\pi n -0.1852)\\nonumber \\\\ &\\quad   +  0.2942 \\cos(0.8 \\pi n -1.4488) \\nonumber\\\\ &\\quad   +\\ 0.1223 \\cos(0.85 \\pi n)  \\end{align}"/></div> has frequencies that are all multiples of <img class="ITS_TEX" src="/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?\\hat\\omega_0=0.05\\pi = 2\\pi/40"/>.  As in the continuous-time case, <span class="ITS_HTML">x[n]</span> in <a href="eq:perexample" class="ITS_reference">&raquo;</a>  has harmonics of the normalized fundamental frequency numbered 2, 4, 5, 16, and 17.','13','12','1');
